\begin{abstract}
The Koide combination $Q = (\sum m_i)/(\sum \sqrt{m_i})^2 = 2/3$, observed for the charged lepton pole masses to one part in $10^5$, has motivated numerous extensions to the quark sector. These extensions typically introduce degrees of freedom not present in the original lepton relation---evaluation at non-self renormalization scales, signed square roots, or selection among multiple quark triples---without a systematic accounting of how each degree of freedom inflates the false-positive rate. This note attempts such an accounting for the quark-only case.

A central observation, from a knob-isolation analysis (Table~\ref{tab:phase1}), is that admitting evaluation at non-self renormalization scales lowers both the observed best residual and the median null residual of the Monte Carlo null by orders of magnitude relative to fixed-scale searches; in each configuration the observed residual is typical under the matched null, so closures identified by running are not unusual relative to the search space that generates them. A causal decomposition of running versus trial-count multiplicity is not attempted and would require a matched-complexity comparison we do not perform. We enumerate 12{,}960 trials over 20 quark triples, four sign assignments, and an audited list of physically interpretable evaluation scales, and apply two complementary null models: a generic random-spectrum reference null with full four-loop CRunDec running on every draw, and a measurement-noise null using a parametric bootstrap around the observed spectrum. At full search freedom, observed closures are statistically indistinguishable from noise under both null models ($p \approx 0.5$). Single-triple claims fixed in prior work (Rivero, Cao, and a prior publication by the present author) fare better under the random-spectrum null ($p = 0.002$--$0.040$ in the baseline, $p = 0.004$--$0.016$ for the $(c,b,t)$ at $\mu = m_\tau$ claim across hierarchy-preserving variants); under the bootstrap they remain inside measurement noise except for the $(c,b,t)$ at $\mu = m_\tau$ claim, which has a noticeably lower but still not conventionally small tail probability ($p \approx 0.15$). Sensitivity checks include validation of an initially-considered surrogate running against full four-loop CRunDec (the surrogate did not reproduce the full-CRunDec result at the per-draw level and was not used in the final analysis), a hierarchy-preserving variant of the random-spectrum null, sensitivity to assumed correlation structure in the FLAG/PDG uncertainties, and three alternative priors. The qualitative ranking is stable across all checks. We additionally tabulate the temporal trajectory of $|Q - 2/3|$ across consecutive FLAG/PDG releases as an independent discriminator: the original lepton Koide residual has tracked decreasing $\sigma_Q$ downward since 1981 (Koide's 1981 prediction $m_\tau = 1776.97$~MeV was confirmed within $0.04\sigma$ by the 1996 BES analysis), while the pre-specified quark-side claims with low Model~A tail probabilities have residuals an order of magnitude or more larger than the current $\sigma_Q$ and stable across the past decade of measurement updates.
\end{abstract}


\section{Introduction}
\label{sec:intro}

Koide~\citep{Koide1982,Koide1983} observed that the charged lepton pole masses satisfy
\begin{equation}
Q(e, \mu, \tau) \;\equiv\; \frac{m_e + m_\mu + m_\tau}{\left(\sqrt{m_e} + \sqrt{m_\mu} + \sqrt{m_\tau}\right)^2} \;=\; \frac{2}{3}
\label{eq:koide}
\end{equation}
to a residual of $6.2 \times 10^{-6}$. Extensions of this relation to the quark sector include Rivero~\citep{Rivero2011} for $(s, c, b)$ with signed $\sqrt{m_s}$; Rodejohann and Zhang~\citep{RZ2011} surveying multiple triples; Cao~\citep{Cao2012} for $(c, b, t)$ at self-scales; and Brilliant~\citep{Brilliant2026cbt} for $(c, b, t)$ with $m_c$ evaluated at $\mu = m_\tau$.

Each such extension introduces one or more degrees of freedom relative to the original formula: which triple, which sign pattern for the square roots, which evaluation scale for each mass. The question this note addresses is the standard look-elsewhere question~\citep{GrossVitells2010}: \emph{given the degrees of freedom employed, how often would random or perturbed inputs produce a comparably tight closure?}

We test a specific enumerated search space (Section~\ref{sec:space}) under two specific null models (Section~\ref{sec:mc}); the resulting tail probabilities apply only to that audited search space. The status of the analysis is exploratory with respect to the full enumeration and confirmatory only for claims explicitly fixed in the prior literature.

\paragraph{Terminology.} We report empirical tail probabilities ($p$-values) under specified null models. These are not severity assessments in the sense of Mayo~\citep{Mayo1996,MayoSpanos2006}: severity is the attained power computed under an alternative hypothesis and is a distinct quantity~\citep{CousinsLectures}. We use ``$p$-value'' exclusively.


\section{Search space}
\label{sec:space}

\subsection{Inputs}

$\overline{\text{MS}}$ quark masses are taken from FLAG~2024~\citep{FLAG2024} and PDG~2024~\citep{PDG2024}:

